< text>
Pizza is good, my wife likes it better than I; but both of us were very unhappy today.   My favorite part is their coke machine, only type of machine I get diet caffeine-free vanilla creme coke, or diet cherry or orange hi-c or minute maid.
Requested for them to refill the diet sweetener portion since all diet drinks were out.  Waited 25 minutes, asked again if they are going to refill coke machine, answer was "not sure."

Then to-go sausage/pepperoni for my son and his friends arrived.  This requested to be in a to-go box.   But was server as dine-in.  No box, and took almost 15 minutes for them to give me a box, every time I went to counter to request box, the cashier said she will bring one.   On the 3rd attempt, finally I received a box.

My wife is ok with meat toppings so she had one slice from the to-go pizza.

Our dine-in cheese pizza finally came out 40 minutes after we ordered, but in a to-go box???

My wife had already finished by this time.   So for me, water to drink after paying for a Coke, (Note, they offered a refund, but I refused hoping they would replace the diet sweetener in the machine), and our pizza finally came out after my wife was ready to leave.

Added after reading other reviews, our cashier was not rude at all, she was a little clueless and didn't listen well, but definitely was not rude.< /text>

Have ordered lunches for our staff from Fresh Brothers about 5 times.  Staff is friendly, curbside service for pick up was great and staff loved their pizzas (choice is fantastic & individuals are generous)  However, twice I ordered a salad for myself. Second time, trying again, we asked nicely if my salad (again BBQ Chicken) could be on DRY lettuce and explained the problem.  Just opened the salad.  So wet it is inedible, like soggy seaweed. <Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
I live in the Midwest and have been spending one month in Santa Barbara.  I have recently been diagnosed with an arthritic hip and did not want to delay physical therapy until I returned home in March.  Hayashida & Associates worked quickly and efficiently with my health care provider and with my health insurance company to arrange physical therapy in a timely manner.  I was very impressed with how they accommodated me as an out-of-town client.  My treatment by Jon Sakota was exceptional.  Complications arose immediately because of acute pain I was experiencing.  Jon listened carefully to my concerns and observed me carefully and saw that I needed to see a specialist before proceeding with therapy.  Jon referred me to a local orthopedist, who saw me the next day to address the issue of my pain.  I cannot say enough positive things about the help I received from Jon Sakota.  I was so fortunate to be able to work with him.  I highly recommend Jon as a skilled and empathetic physical therapist.<//Text>

< Review>
I couldn't be more pleased with my experience at Hayashida PT, and with my "hero" there, Jason.  I was referred there through my doctor and insurance to treat intense tingling and some pain in my left arm.  About 10 years ago, before moving to Santa Barbara,  I experienced pain in my right shoulder and pectoral muscle,  which was ascribed [via MRI/X-ray examination] to cervical stenosis [i.e. deterioration of the spine at the neck].  While PT solved that immediate problem,  the doctor warned that the long term prognosis was for more serious problems.  So I was pessimistic that the tingling could be due to a pinched nerve at the neck and would require surgery,  something I dreaded,  given my understanding that surgery on the spine can go awry.  Jason reassured me that there was a good probability that stretching and loosening the neck joints [via his manipulation of the neck and assigned exercises] could solve the problem,  and it did!
Further,  the facility on Anacapa St. is pleasant,  quieter and more organized than  some other PT operations I've used over the years.</Review>

The service: My first alignment (my third appointment, because the first was in house x-rays and the second was setting a game plan to recovery) was by far the best sensation I have ever experienced, it was almost an emotional release, and it really felt like things were being put in place ‚ú® gently ‚ú®. < Review>
My husband's 85 Celica started acting up an hour after we started heading home in our vacation. Certified II Car Repair was able to not only get us in same day, but immediately. They were able to diagnose the suspected issue (blown alternator) and already had the part on the way before talking to us, to expedite the process. We were there and gone in roughly 2 hours. In our dealings, and the ones we overheard, they were fair, direct and courteous. And put up with a screaming bird. Based on this one interaction, I'd highly recommend them. As a female, I appreciated the feeling that they would have dealt with me straight.< /Review>

< Review>
I checked out other auto repair shops before choosing Certified Auto ll. I thought Cody, whom I initially spoke with on the phone, to be pleasant. I told him that I may need the fuel pump replaced in my car but wasn't sure.
He gave me his thoughts on what might be wrong but I would have to come in for an inspection. He said that it might even be something as minor as a broken fuse under the dash that mimics a broken pump.( I don't want to mix words. I can't remember how he explained the two, but he did let me know that it could be either or). I appreciated that so I chose his shop.
After the inspection, we were told that it was the fuel pump. The next day he said that a few other things were found n my husband agreed to have them fixed.
When I went to pick up the car, I noticed the master window switch was lying on the floor. I told Tim, another employee, about it n said that someone in his shop had broken it. It WAS NOT broken prior. He said that he would have it fixed n to come back the next day.
I also felt that the car was running kind of rough, so I told them when I took it back the next day. The shop kept it until the next afternoon. I was told that three employees had driven the car n did not find it to run rough. The switch still had not been fixed.
I also saw the TV that is attached to the roof of the car was hanging, n later fell!
That TV was used VERY little. In fact, the original film on the screen was still on it!
I spoke to Cody about the TV n the master switch n told him that three windows would not roll up due to the switch n that someone had pulled the TV down n it also had fallen.
Cody informed me that I would need to speak to Tim about the switch n that his shop has been in business over thirty years n no one would break or mess with anything. He said they could replace the switch but it would cost ME $505.00!
Again I told him that his shop broke it but evidently he did not believe me.
California Sound, whom I bought the TV from, reattached the TV n let the windows up for me....for free!
Needless to say, I will not go back to Certified Auto ll, nor will I recommend it to anyone.
I am not prone to being dishonest n I always give compliments n good reviews to whoever deserves praise for their work. Where there is poor or dishonest service, people need to know.
This is/was my experience with Certified Auto ll n my review.</Review>

< text>
They do what you ask, but they do not go above and beyond, and attempt to scare you to getting unnecessary things repaired.

My clutch went out on my 2001 Subaru Forester. I was referred to Certified II by a local new car dealer, so I figured they would be reputable for Subarus. I called them on a Friday morning to see if and when they can get it done. On the phone I was quoted $1100, and it could be done by the end of the next day if I brought it in by closing. $1100 is more than I had wanted to pay, but they were referred by the biggest dealer in the area, they must be the best, right?

I brought the car in by the end of the day.  In addition to replacing the clutch, they suggested I replace the rack and pinion (quoted $919), as well as the cylinder head gaskets (quoted $1500).  I knew ahead of time that the power steering was whining because of a leak, and of COURSE the head gaskets are leaking. ALL SUBARUS HAVE LEAKY HEAD GASKETS! I have no white or blue exhaust, and there are no indications that this is out of the Subaru-norm.

They tried to scare me into getting the other things taken care of. I declined both of these add-ons because, adding up all three quotes, it would cost me $3500 to repair my car!?  I can get another 2001 Forester for that amount!  Go ahead on the clutch.

They replaced it by TUESDAY, which is three days past the promised day of "NEXT DAY."  They gave me no excuse or apology for not getting it done by their projected date.  It was extremely inconvenient.

When I picked it up, the guy up front said, "what was your quoted price again?"  And I said, "$1100."  For funsies he went ahead and wrote up the bill reflecting that, instead of actually calculating.

He decided to throw in another $99. A sublet repair for resurfacing the flywheel for $80?  They don't need to sublet that,they can do it there OR, GET ME A NEW FLYWHEEL FOR $60! His numbers seemed arbitrary, like it was normal to add on something extra to see what he can get. I paid it. I don't want to replace the clutch myself, it would take me two weeks of trial and error.  I was happy to have a good, working, safe car for my 8 month old to ride in, even if I had to take out a small loan to get it done.

About 500 miles later, the clutch pedal starting sticking. It didn't happen all the time, but when it did stick, it prevented it from completely returning back to normal position, though was still 100% functional. Since I have no idea about clutches and clutch pedals, I called them and they said they'd take a look if I brought it in that day.

When I brought it in, the mechanic said there was a small leak near the clutch master cylinder that caused the pedal to stick.  He showed me the leak, which was TINY. And could have, should have easily been REPLACED WHEN THEY DID THE CLUTCH.  They went ahead and added some fluid to and sent me off with a quote for $158.  I decided to skip that repair.  Something seemed fishy.  I angrily drove home with still a sticking pedal....

At home I fiddled around with the pedal and watched the hose that "leaks." I couldn't find the leak. Instead I got under the dash to see if something was odd, and I noticed something really dumb. The clutch pedal was sticking to the floor mat.  Moved the floor mat, problem IMMEDIATELY FIXED.  Nice job, Certified II. Trying to find some reason for the sticking clutch, they just pointed at something that looked wrong and decided that was the reason.

My power steering kept whining more and more, and with the fluid indicator saying the reservoir was full, I decided to take it to a different mechanic to diagnose it.

Diagnosis?

Rack and pinion is FINE. This leak is smaller than a pin hole, in the power steering pressure line hose. The mechanic said to keep an eye on it, but to refill the fluid as necessary. The reservoir drinks the fluid as it's added, so it looks full even when not. The quote from that mechanic was $280 including labor.

Long story short: they will fix what you ask, but not go out of their way.  They price gouge.  They try to scare you into unnecessary repairs.</text>

< text>
I dropped off a pad to have a new charging port put in, They said it would take 3 to 5 days so I left it with them . On the 5th day I hadn't heard from them so I called them and they said the part had to be ordered and it would be another 5 days. By this time it's close to the end of the month and I'm on disability so I'm getting low on funds, I still had the money for the pad but it was about all I had, so I asked if I could pick it up on the first which was 2 days away and the guy began telling me the storage policy then put me on hold to speak with a manager.  When he returned to the call he said it would be fine. It had already been a really difficult last couple of months for me, on Feb 4th I had to report my girlfriend missing to the l.b.p.d. and my entire life was a wash, I've been beside myself,  I can't think, eat, sleep or basically function at all, as I said I'm already on disability and have many physical and mental problems.  I went in there to pick up the person said I would have to come back later in the day because it was a separate company, which I wasn't made aware of on the calls, I didn't know I had to be there at a certain time and he could tell I was already stressed and told me to hold on as he went into the back. A few minutes later a different guy comes out and is basically upset he had to come out early to give my pad back, and obviously I could see he wasn't happy but I just wanted my pad so I could get out of there and go home, and I did. I received the pad and asked for a bag to put it in because I had a mini laptop as well and I put both in the bag making sure the pad screen was on the outside. When I got home I took the pad out, and they had put one of those films over the scene,  like when you get a new phone it comes with the plastic film over the sceen, this one wasn't new so the film was all bubbly and you really couldn't see the sceen that well. As I took the film off I was shocked to see that the screen was hit or dropped, because it has a very specific hit point then is cracked from that hit point all the way to the other side of the screen.  There is no way this could have happened in that bag on a short walk home. Obviously I should have checked it in the store, but most places are always eager to show you the product they fixed for you, They want you to see it for yourself before you leave, They made no effort at all to do this in any way. When I called I was again told about the separate company and told to call back. I eventually spoke with the person and told them what had happened and he said they could fix it at whatever they would normally charge for that and truly seemed like he was teaching me a lesson,  I should have looked at it before I left he said several times, laughing and then becoming upset , totally unprofessional.  As I looked closer at my pad I see that they cut one corner with a knife or something,  it's all gapped up, to take the screen off I guess.  I have never dropped this pad ,ever, and there's a dent like mark on the same corner as the crack. < text>
My family loves Buca. We typically come for birthdays, we've come for Xmas and Thanksgiving with the whole extended family. Everyone always really enjoys the food. It's nice to go with a bigger party so you can get more options with the family style service. My son loves the ravioli with meat sauce, my mom loves the fettuccine, my dad and I love the carbonara, everyone loves the manicotti, canneloni, salads and warm bread. Because we usually spend birthdays here we're always treated with huge cakes and brownies and piles of ice cream, it's very tasty and makes the celebration more special.
I'd recommend this place for any special occasion or just a delicious family style meal with your home. They do great with take out orders and have curbside available. There's constantly great deals running with their eclub so join that before you go or check your email for deals. We really enjoyed the 50% off orders of ravioli for national ravioli day 2021!! A large order with salad and bread was enough for my family of 4 to eat once for dinner and once for lunch!</text>

<Time>1577247925302< /Time><rating>5<//rating><text>Excellent service

We celebrated our wedding with Buca di Beppo in Huntington Beach and it was amazing. From our first encounter with Alfonso, our experience was awesome. He was easy to reach and always available. Alfonso helped the process flow as easy as possible. From menu changes, time changes and decorations, we never had an issue. Alfonso was always so willing to help meet our accomodations. Thank you Alfonso for everything you have done. We grately appreciate it.

The day of our event, we were an hour earlier than expected, yet the staff was so willing to still seat and serve us. The manager Gabby, was in charge during our event and we were very pleased. Our party played music and we're a little loud, yet the managers approach was very professional. Thank you Gabby for being such a great host.

Our head server Tina, Kylie and Augustine were amazing. Our party guest never went with an empty cup and always full of food. With our guest count, they were fast and extremely patient with our extra needs. Very grateful for their services on a day that meant so much to us.

Thank you Buca di Beppo for such an amazing time. Looking forward to host more events with you guys.<//text>< pics>

< Text>
Everything is family style here. One small serving of pasta is what I would make for my family of 4 for dinner. My visit was for a party of 8. We got fried mozzarella, salad and breschetta pre-meal. <name>Joel Garcia</name><date>1542649944965<//date>< text>
We visited this restaurant with a mixed group, four adults and young two children. The service was great, servers were very friendly and accommodating to every member of my family. For a large place the noise volume was good. Because of our mixed group, we ordered a simple meal, spaghetti and meatballs and an order of baked ziti. The meal was fine, but I would not order it again. The colossal brownie sundae was very tasty and hit the spot; oh, the coffee is good as well. My wife and I will come back and try something different rather than the same old pasta dishes, maybe the salmon sorrento or the chicken saltimbocca. I was thinking about this. Why go to an Italian restaurant and order something you can make yourself that is great? Try something new.< /text>

< Review>
So apparently there's no Buca di Beppo in south orange county anymore? That's a shame.. but I'm assuming it's because of the way their resturant is designed.  For a couple, you end up spending way too much money on two small entrees to share. On top of this, a lot of people hate sharing food so I understand why it wouldn't work out.

They need to work on establishing a happy hour, and taking mobile coupons because no one prints coupons anymore and I've been turned away from them because I had a mobile coupon.</Review>

< Text>
I know this is a chain and once up a time they had decent food. I am DONE with chains.

They prepare the food in their warehouse kitchen and transport the food to their various locations. Upon arrival the resturants heat the food to the desired temperature. I feel like I am paying  to eat frozen.

Our lasagne was icy cold in the middle and the pasta was sogging. The salads were wilted  and smell. Our party of 15 +,  was polite about the food most carried it home and threw it out.

The manager was rude; he told us to leave because we were there to long. Now, we  were in the middle of ordering  after dinner drinks and desserts.  No, our group was disruptive or loud. We even  put out the fire on the table next to us.

May 19, 2018, was a celebration of my neice's birthday and celebrating her graduation from college.</Text>

At one time this was (Buca in general not just this location) one of my favorite places to have Italian.  Over the last ten years or so what you get has decreased while their prices have increased. <time>1446585998867</time><Text>Good food served family-style & fast service!</Text><user_id>105873089388963225014< /user_id>< Name>
Joey Bauer</Name>
<GmapID>0x80dd2642223c9b3f:0xffdd17e1fb8e2ba5</GmapID>< pics>

</record>
</dataset><record>
< name>
Brian Bergstr√∂m</name>
<gmap_id>0x80dd2642223c9b3f:0xffdd17e1fb8e2ba5< /gmap_id><Date>1338711203361<//Date>< review>
We were treated to a dinner here last week and it is just lousy. I remembered why I hate Buca di Beppos.

First we ate in the Pope Room, as a Catholic I can say it is kinda weird... I mean I can appreciate all of it. But since I am guessing most people are not Catholic dedicating a room to the Pope is odd. In fact we were among the last to arrive in the party and the poor protestants we were supping with had already had the bust of Pope John Paul II removed from the room. I have seen it before, and having the Pope's head in the middle of a lazy Susan is kind of creepy.

We were a large party, but that doesn't excuse the slow service, it is not like we didn't have reservations. Or that since there is a room constantly booked for large parties, they should be properly staffed for it. Especially if when it gets close to the time for the next party they are rushing you out. Come on, if it didn't take forever to bring the order we'd be gone naturally.

Food was poor to mediocre at best. The selections were Spaghetti and demolished meatball pieces, Chicken Parmesan and Pasta Alfredo. The Alfredo was simply inedible, how can you go wrong with pouring a box of Spaghetti into boiling water and the Chicken was actually edible. There was also a salad and horrible cheesecake type something. It didn't taste like any cheesecake I have ever had. There was no crust, and tasted like it was missing salt and other ingredients that bring out the flavor. Maybe it was some kind of healthy, sugar free, salt free, gluten free dessert substitute.

So I was seated near the host so I saw the bill, so for 3 bowls of salad, 3 bowls of each of the 3 entrees, and 18 slices of wannabe cheesecake it was $568 including tax and tip with soft drinks for some of the people.  No alcohol that I saw was served. That's more than $31 per person!!! Sorry I would've come a little unglued if I were paying for that... For $50 I could go to Costco and buy a lot more and better frozen Italian food that could be thrown in the oven and taste 100x better. Even pick up a $6 box of garlic bread with 27 slices. Yeah I would have to work a little to cook it, but for $500 it would be worth it.

Parking was awful, we circled twice and were late to the dinner, so we just parked in the "to go"  spot, nobody said anything.

One last humorous event, before the kicked us out, someone stopped by with a digital camera and had everyone bunch up on the far side of the dirty table and took a picture. Then came back with 4 pictures with a Buca di Beppo's border around them and said we could buy the pictures (which are going in the trash if we didn't anyway) for $10 each. Really??? We took pictures at the event ourselves and for a couple dollars I could print everyone at the table 8x10 photos if they wanted.<//review>

<rate>3< /rate>< review>
We were treated to a dinner here last week and it is just lousy. I remembered why I hate Buca di Beppos.

First we ate in the Pope Room, as a Catholic I can say it is kinda weird... I mean I can appreciate all of it. But since I am guessing most people are not Catholic dedicating a room to the Pope is odd. In fact we were among the last to arrive in the party and the poor protestants we were supping with had already had the bust of Pope John Paul II removed from the room. I have seen it before, and having the Pope's head in the middle of a lazy Susan is kind of creepy.

We were a large party, but that doesn't excuse the slow service, it is not like we didn't have reservations. Or that since there is a room constantly booked for large parties, they should be properly staffed for it. Especially if when it gets close to the time for the next party they are rushing you out. Come on, if it didn't take forever to bring the order we'd be gone naturally.

Food was poor to mediocre at best. The selections were Spaghetti and demolished meatball pieces, Chicken Parmesan and Pasta Alfredo. The Alfredo was simply inedible, how can you go wrong with pouring a box of Spaghetti into boiling water and the Chicken was actually edible. There was also a salad and horrible cheesecake type something. It didn't taste like any cheesecake I have ever had. There was no crust, and tasted like it was missing salt and other ingredients that bring out the flavor. Maybe it was some kind of healthy, sugar free, salt free, gluten free dessert substitute.

So I was seated near the host so I saw the bill, so for 3 bowls of salad, 3 bowls of each of the 3 entrees, and 18 slices of wannabe cheesecake it was $568 including tax and tip with soft drinks for some of the people.  No alcohol that I saw was served. That's more than $31 per person!!! Sorry I would've come a little unglued if I were paying for that... For $50 I could go to Costco and buy a lot more and better frozen Italian food that could be thrown in the oven and taste 100x better. Even pick up a $6 box of garlic bread with 27 slices. Yeah I would have to work a little to cook it, but for $500 it would be worth it.

Parking was awful, we circled twice and were late to the dinner, so we just parked in the "to go"  spot, nobody said anything.

One last humorous event, before the kicked us out, someone stopped by with a digital camera and had everyone bunch up on the far side of the dirty table and took a picture. Then came back with 4 pictures with a Buca di Beppo's border around them and said we could buy the pictures (which are going in the trash if we didn't anyway) for $10 each. Really??? We took pictures at the event ourselves and for a couple dollars I could print everyone at the table 8x10 photos if they wanted.<//review>
